<TITLE> Power agreement to be expedited </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Thimphu, April 29 (bdnews24.com)--Bangladesh and India have agreed to expedite the implementation of the agreements signed during the prime minister's January visit to Delhi, including one on power sector cooperation. At a meeting on Thursday between Sheikh Hasina and the Indian premier Manmohan Singh, the two leaders also agreed to work together to try and get the Sundarbans chosen as one of the 'wonders' of the world. "The two leaders have stressed implementation of the four agreements and the MoU signed during our prime minister's Delhi visit," Abul Kalam Azad, prime minister's press secretary, told bdnews24.com Thursday after the meeting on Thursday. The two premiers met at around 10.45 am on the sidelines of the SAARC summit at the village in the Bhutanese capital erected for housing the eight top leaders of South Asia. The Bangladesh prime minister had earlier met the Pakistan prime minister on Apr 27. In January, Dhaka and Delhi signed four accords including a memorandum of understanding on Cooperation in the Power Sector. As per the deal, power-starved Bangladesh will import power from India. The power ministries of the two countries have already started discussing the modalities of importing energy through linking their two power grids. The two countries also signed the Agreement on Mutual Legal Assistance on Criminal Matters, Agreement on the Transfer of Sentenced Persons, Agreement on Combating International Terrorism, Organized Crime and Illicit Drug Trafficking and the Agreement on Cultural Exchange Programme
